# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: the-new-york-times
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] From March 9 to June 5, 1920, voters of the Republican Party elected delegates to the 1920 Republican National Convention for the purpose of choosing the party's nominee for president in the 1920 election.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The delegates were largely contested between Governor Hiram Johnson of California, a progressive who had been the running mate of Theodore Roosevelt eight years prior; General Leonard Wood, one of Roosevelt's closest friends; and Frank O.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] After a series of primary elections and caucuses, no candidate had emerged with a clear majority of the delegates.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] At the 1920 Republican National Convention, held from June 8 to June 12, in Chicago, Illinois, the delegations of the leading candidates deadlocked and Warren G.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Harding was nominated as a dark horse candidate, although he had only won a few delegates entering the convention.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In 1912, the Republican Party was split.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Former President Theodore Roosevelt challenged incumbent William Howard Taft for the nomination and, when it was denied at the 1912 Republican National Convention, bolted to form the Progressive Party.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With Republicans (who had won eight of the previous eleven presidential elections) split, Woodrow Wilson won the race with a plurality of the popular vote and a large majority in the electoral college.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In 1916, the Republican Party nominated Associate Justice of the United States Charles Evans Hughes, a respected jurist and former Governor of New York, as one who could appeal to both Progressives and Republicans alike.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Though Hughes was able to avoid disaster when Roosevelt declined to run on the Progressive ticket, he fell narrowly short of defeating President Wilson, who significantly improved on his vote from 1912.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The campaign was dominated by two wars: the Mexican Revolution and World War I.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Responding to Republican calls for military preparedness, Wilson used the slogan "He kept us out of war" to emphasize the maintenance of U.S. neutrality.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In January 1917, the Zimmermann telegram from Germany to Mexico was intercepted by British intelligence.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In the telegram, German diplomat Arthur Zimmermann offered to restore much of the territory Mexico had lost in the Mexican–American War in the event the United States entered the war.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Zimmermann, hoping to threaten the United States, admitted the telegram's authenticity in a March speech to the Reichstag.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Public outcry ensued, and Wilson requested a declaration of a "war to end all wars" against Germany.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Congress granted the request on April 6, 1917, shortly after Wilson began his second term and nearly three years after the war had begun.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Major General Frederick Funston, Wilson's first choice to command U.S. forces, had died in February.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Several Republican Party leaders called on Wilson to appoint Leonard Wood, a close friend and advisor of Theodore Roosevelt and long-time preparedness advocate.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Pershing, a Republican who had previously gained fame as commander of the Pancho Villa Expedition, at the behest of Secretary of War Newton D.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] After a yearlong mobilization effort, Pershing and U.S. troops began major combat operations during summer 1918, near the war's end.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The United States was able to claim victory with relatively few casualties.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Pershing's fame was further elevated to that of a war hero.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He was widely considered a candidate for the presidency, though some Republicans considered him too close to the Wilson administration.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] On January 8, 1918, Wilson delivered a speech to Congress specifying his war aims.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Those idealist aims, which came to be known as Wilson's Fourteen Points, sought to expand his progressive domestic program abroad.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The Fourteen Points were to serve as the basis for negotiation of the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Among the most controversial points were his proposals to remove economic barriers between nations, guarantee national self-determination, and establish a League of Nations, an international body designed to prevent future wars.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Criticism of the Fourteen Points as idealistic or an abrogation of national sovereignty was a major focus of the Republican campaign of 1918.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The leading critic was former President Theodore Roosevelt, by now the early favorite for the 1920 presidential nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Though Roosevelt himself had privately predicted 1916 was his last campaign, his public profile remained strong and his attacks on Wilson made him a natural contender.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, Roosevelt's had physical condition deteriorated rapidly after his son Quentin was killed in action in July, and he died at the age of sixty on January 6, 1919.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His final written work, a criticism of the proposed League of Nations and defense of "Americanism," was published in *Metropolitan Magazine* shortly after his death.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With the war in its final weeks, Americans elected the Republican Party to control of both houses of Congress.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In the state elections, Republicans performed well in the West, gaining five governors' offices west of the Mississippi River.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Their major loss came in Roosevelt's home of New York, where Al Smith gained the governor's office.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With Roosevelt dead, the leading candidates for the nomination were his friend, General Wood, and Senator Warren G.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] On February 9, 1919, Wood delivered a memorial address for Roosevelt, in which he echoed the late President's criticisms of the League of Nations and raised his own national profile as a political orator.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Having lost command of Congress, Wilson left to personally represent the United States at the Paris Peace Conference in January 1919; he was the first President to leave for Europe while still in office.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He brought with him only one Republican and chose, rather than a Senator or Representative, the ex-diplomat Henry White.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The success of the Bolshevik Revolution and the threat of revolution in Germany, Austria, and Italy bred hope and fear for revolution in the United States, where the Socialist Party had made modest gains.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With Wilson in Europe and Roosevelt dead, the country was leaderless, as were both of its major political parties.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Labor strikes in 1919, especially in New York and Seattle, startled conservatives.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Further strikes rocked the textile industry, the clothing trade, and street railcars.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The 1919 Boston police strike skyrocketed Massachusetts governor Calvin Coolidge to national prominence when, amid rioting and looting, he sternly declared there was no right "to strike against the public safety." Frank O.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Lowden of Illinois also came to prominence for his handling of the Chicago race riot of 1919, facing off with mayor William Hale Thompson in a game of brinksmanship.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Leonard Wood made his personal contribution to the counterrevolution by leading his troops to West Virginia in April, where they headed off armed miners without resorting to violence.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In September, Wood led troops to suppress a race riot in Omaha, brought on by the lynching of a black civilian.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Again, he restored the peace without further bloodshed.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His most controversial political act came in October, when he attempted to mediate the general steel strike of 1919.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The mediation ultimately failed, but Wood imposed terms on the strikers and capital with pleased neither.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Between his domestic deployments in 1919, Wood traveled the country speaking on behalf of veterans' organizations.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Everywhere, he was received as if he were already the Republican nominee.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] King, a former associate of Roosevelt's from Bridgeport, Connecticut, as a political manager.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Others in the party's Old Guard, however, saw Wood as too independent and preferred Harding.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] By November 1919, Wood's political-military campaign had been a rousing success.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] "Unless the situation changes," wrote William Allen White, "no other candidate will be mentioned in the Republican Convention.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] But the situation of course in this country will have to be desperate if it does not change." As the popular front-runner, Wood was vulnerable both from fatigue and the attention of other candidates, led first by Harding.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The following candidates stood for nomination in their home states for the purpose of controlling their delegate slate at the convention.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] They did not receive the first-ballot support of delegates in more than two other states or territories.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Though he was among the stronger potential candidates, Harding intended from the start to run a low-key campaign that would position himself as the alternative to the chaotic open field left by Roosevelt's death.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] As he told campaign manager Frank Scobey, "It has been my own judgment not to go at it too vigorously in order to reach the high tide of our publicity movement until late in the campaign.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] There were at least ten serious contenders at the onset of the campaign: Wood, Harding, Lowden, Coolidge, California governor Hiram Johnson, Howard Sutherland, Pennsylvania governor William Cameron Sproul, Miles Poindexter, Herbert Hoover, and Nicholas Murray Butler.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, the Lowden campaign declined to pursue any binding delegate elections and instead sought to persuade uncommitted and uninstructed delegates after their election.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] One of the key contests came late in April in Harding's home state of Ohio, which he would absolutely need to carry to stand any chance at the nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Wood's supporters in the state, led by William C.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Procter, surprised Harding by entering the general's name for the primary rather than letting Harding's status as a favorite son go unchallenged.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Procter offered to withdraw Wood's name on the condition that he be declared the second choice of the Ohio delegates, but Harding flatly refused.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Wood hit the state with a barnstorming tour, dressed in his military uniform and echoing Roosevelt's progressivism.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Harding was so confident in winning Ohio that he left the state early to campaign in Indiana.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, the result was a narrow victory over Wood, closer than anyone expected.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The Indiana primary was among the most sharply contested of the campaign, featuring four serious candidates in Wood, Lowden, Harding, and Hiram Johnson.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Harding had been convinced to enter the primary by Senator Harry New, one of his closest allies in the Senate.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Harding finished fourth with only nine percent of the vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Having been humiliated in the only two primaries he contested outside his home state, Harding strongly considered withdrawing to focus on his re-election to the Senate.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Instead, his wife convinced him to remain in the race and leverage his status as the Ohio candidate, as others had done before him, and win the nomination on a later ballot.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His strategy now focused on becoming the "available man" in the event of a deadlock, securing secondary commitments from delegates who favored Wood, Lowden, or Johnson.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] On the eve of the convention, no man had secured enough support for the nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, Wood and Lowden suffered a major blow when the Senate investigation into campaign expenditures was published.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Kenyon revealed massive spending by both Wood and Lowden's campaigns, including two canceled checks from Lowden to Missouri delegates that could not be explained.
[src:the-new-york-times/1920-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Johnson was indirectly damaged by the investigation as well, since Wood and Lowden supporters blamed him for instigating it; the enmity between the front-runners appeared to ensure none could secure the others' support.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] The **1927 New York Yankees season** was the 25th season of the New York Yankees of the American League.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] The team finished with a record of 110–44–1 (the team's first 100 win season), winning their fifth pennant and finishing 19 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics and were tied for first or better for the whole season.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] New York was managed by Miller Huggins, and played at Yankee Stadium.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] They won the 1927 World Series, sweeping the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] This Yankees team was known for its feared lineup, which was nicknamed "Murderers' Row", and is widely considered to be the greatest baseball team in MLB history.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig finished the 1927 season with 12.6 and 11.9 Wins Above Replacement (WAR), respectively.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] These totals are among the top ten highest single-season WAR by a player in MLB history, with Ruth's 12.6 ranking third (behind his 12.8 WAR in 1921 and 14.1 WAR in 1923) and Gehrig's 11.9 ranking sixth.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] The Yankees' 110 victories broke the previous American League mark of 105 (set by the 1912 Boston Red Sox) and would stand as the American League single-season record until it was broken by the Cleveland Indians in 1954.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] But counting their World Series sweep, the 1927 Yankees had a total record of 114–44 --- which is still the all-time highest single-season winning percentage (.721) in American League history.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] The 1998 Yankees, who also won their World Series in a sweep, are second with a full-season mark of 125–50 (.714).
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] This was the first year the Yankees acknowledged their team nickname on their uniforms, albeit their *road* uniforms.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Their home uniforms remained free of any kind of logo except for the "NY" on their caps.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] The roster included nine future Hall of Famers: Pitchers Herb Pennock and Waite Hoyt, Infielders Lou Gehrig and Tony Lazzeri, outfielders Babe Ruth and Earle Combs, Manager Miller Huggins, Team President Ed Barrow and Owner Colonel Jacob Ruppert.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] With the race long since decided, the nation's attention turned to Babe Ruth's pursuit of his own home run mark of 59, set in 1921.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Early in the season, Ruth expressed doubts about his chances: "I don't suppose I'll ever break that 1921 record.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] To do that, you've got to start early, and the pitchers have got to pitch to you.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] I don't start early, and the pitchers haven't really pitched to me in four seasons.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] I get more bad balls to hit than any other five men...and fewer good ones." Ruth was also being challenged for his slugger's crown by teammate Lou Gehrig, who nudged ahead of Ruth's total in midseason, prompting the *New York World-Telegram* to anoint Gehrig the favorite.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] But Ruth caught Gehrig (who would finish with 47), and then had a remarkable last leg of the season, hitting 17 home runs in September.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] His 60th came on September 30, in the Yankees' next-to-last game against the Washington Senators at Yankee Stadium.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Tied 2–2, he hit a 2-run home run in the bottom of the 8th inning off of Tom Zachary, where they won the game 4–2.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Ruth was exultant, shouting after the game, "Sixty, count 'em, sixty!
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Let's see some other son of a bitch match that!" In later years, he would give Gehrig some credit: "Pitchers began pitching to me because if they passed me they still had Lou to contend with." In addition to his career-high 60 home runs, Ruth batted .356, drove in 165 runs and slugged .772.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Since a voter could select only one player per team, two good candidates from the same team could find their votes split and both of their chances of winning hurt.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] In addition, the clause prohibiting repeat winners led to unusual results like Babe Ruth's 1927 (one of the greatest offensive seasons of all time) not being eligible for the award.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] Through Myles Thomas's diary entries, additional essays and real-time social-media components (including Twitter) "re-living" that famous Yankees season, the goal is to explore the rarefied nexus of baseball, jazz and Prohibition — defining elements of the remarkable world that existed in 1927.
[src:the-new-york-times/1927-new-york-yankees-season] The diary runs the length of the full 1927 season, from April 13 through October 10, 1927.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The **1962–1963 New York City newspaper strike** was a strike action within the newspaper industry of New York City which ran from December 8, 1962 until March 31, 1963, lasting for a total of 114 days.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Besides protesting low wages, the unions were resisting automation of the printing presses.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The strike played a pivotal role in changing the attitude of the public to daily newspapers, leading to the demise of some papers and paved the way for new print publications and the start of all-news radio in the New York Metropolitan Area.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] A preliminary action took place when The Newspaper Guild went on strike against the *Daily News* just after midnight on November 1, 1962.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Murphy indicated that the *Daily News* had been singled out as the union's first target "because there we have had more aggravation, more agitation, more issues, more disputes and more anti-unionism from management".
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *Daily News* was able to keep printing on November 2, 1962 by using the presses of the *New York Journal-American*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Workers at the *Daily News* settled their issues, accepting raises of $8 per week in talks mediated by United States Secretary of Labor W.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Willard Wirtz, with employees receiving an added $4.25 per week in the first year, with an additional $3.75 weekly in the subsequent year, allowing the paper to start with a print run of 1.5 million copies, short of its nation-leading normal circulation of 2,075,000 copies.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] On December 4, 1962, negotiators representing the nine major newspapers offered a deal that combined an $8 increase in wages and benefits spread over two years, combined with changes in work procedures that would cut costs for the papers.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Union negotiators rejected the offer from the newspapers the following day, setting their requirement of a $16 weekly raise over two years, and set a deadline of midnight on December 8 if an agreement could not be reached before then.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Representatives of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service, including Frank H.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Brown and Stephen Schlossberg, attempted to help both sides reach agreement on December 6, with "the public interest" cited as justifying federal intervention.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The strike began at 2 a.m. on December 8, when workers from the New York local of the International Typographical Union, led by their president Bert Powers, walked out from the *Daily News*, *New York Journal-American*, *The New York Times*, and *New York World-Telegram & Sun*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] In addition, the *New York Daily Mirror*, *New York Herald Tribune*, *New York Post,* the *Long Island Star Journal,* and the *Long Island Daily Press* all suspended operations on a voluntary basis.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The newspapers kept their offer of an $8 increase per week spread over two years, while the unions were looking for a $38.82 increase in the two-year period.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] A number of publications were created or benefited from the strike.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] *The New York Review of Books* was created during the strike, issuing its first copies on February 21, 1963, with circulation reaching 75,000 during the strike, before retreating to between 50,000 and 60,000 following the strike.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *Brooklyn Eagle* saw circulation grow from 50,000 to 390,000 before shrinking to 154,000 before it was hit with a separate deliverers' strike on June 27, 1963.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Fortunato Pope, publisher of the Italian-language daily newspaper *Il Progresso Italo-Americano*, launched an English-language tabloid called the *New York Daily Report*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] WABC-FM adopted a prototypical all-news radio format during the 114-day strike, preceding WINS as the first station with an all-news format in New York City.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Other substitute newspapers were *The New York Daily Report* and *The New York Metropolitan Daily*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Four papers had originally been the target of the strike, but five other papers suspended printing on a voluntary basis.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *New York Post* was able to resume printing on March 4, 1963, by withdrawing from the Publishers Association: they would be bound by whatever settlement the other papers made, and would have no further voice in negotiating it.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *New York Herald Tribune* published a statement that they had chosen not to resume publishing on the same terms because of the risk that the eventual settlement would put them out of business.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Wagner Jr., and labor negotiator Theodore W.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Kheel were eventually able to forge an agreement to end the strike after several attempts.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The first deal offered for ratification by the printers' union was rejected on March 17.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] In another vote on March 24, they agreed to settle, but by this time the photo engravers' union had decided to join the strike, and they did not settle until March 31.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] As publication resumed, the first headline in the *Daily News* was "We Have News for You".
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The printers would receive wage and benefit increases of $12.63 per week.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Kheel noted that the contracts for all ten newspaper unions would expire on the same date in 1965, emphasizing the importance of addressing the festering labor issues.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] An analysis performed by *The New York Times* showed that the nine affected newspapers lost a total of more than $100 million (equivalent to $1,052 million in 2025) in advertising and circulation revenues and that the industry's more than 19,000 employees lost $50 million in wages and benefits.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] After the strike was ended, both the *Times* and *Herald Tribune* doubled their price to 10 cents, one of the factors that had cut readership.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] As of September 30, 1963, circulation of six daily New York papers was down 11.9% on weekdays and 8.3% on Sundays based on reports from the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Kennedy assassination in November 1963 helped bring readers back to newspapers.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *New York Daily Mirror*, owned by the Hearst Corporation, shut down on October 15, 1963, and sold its name and goodwill to the *Daily News*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1962-1963-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *Mirror's* management blamed the closure on the effects of the strike aggravating existing problems at the paper.
[src:the-new-york-times/1976-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The **1976 United States Senate election in New York** was held on November 2, 1976.
[src:the-new-york-times/1976-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Buckley ran for re-election to a second term, but was defeated by Democratic diplomat Pat Moynihan.
[src:the-new-york-times/1976-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] As of 2026, this is the last time an incumbent Senator from New York lost re-election to this Class 1 seat.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The **1978 New York City newspaper strike** ran from August 10 to November 5, 1978, a total of 88 days.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] It affected the New York City newspaper industry, shutting down all three of the city's major newspapers: *The New York Times*, *New York Daily News,* and the *New York Post*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The multi-union strike was led by pressmen and halted production of the three papers, with no editions being published since August 9, 1978.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Other unions who walked out included those for machinists, paperhandlers, truck mechanics, and drivers.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The strike occurred due to the three newspapers each issuing new work rulings which significantly decreased requirements concerning the level of staffing.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Unlike many strikes, wage levels were not a major issue.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] More than 10,000 employees were either striking or out of work in support of one of the striking unions.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] During the outage, several strike papers popped into existence, being sold on newsstands and with bylines from the three regular papers; these included *The City News*, *The New York Daily Press*, and *The New York Daily Metro*.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] One existing paper that momentarily benefited during this time was Unification Church-owned *The News World*, which had been launched in 1976 and reached its highest-ever circulation of 400,000 during the strike; some well-known reporters for the three closed papers wrote for it as well.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Two months into the strike, a parody of *The New York Times* called *Not The New York Times* was distributed in the city, with contributors such as Carl Bernstein, Christopher Cerf, Tony Hendra, and George Plimpton.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Contrary to initial expectations, New York businesses such as restaurants, theaters, hotels, and retail stores did not suffer during the strike, finding alternate ways to advertise their presence and offerings.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] What is sometimes claimed as an unanticipated consequence of the strike was the turnaround in the 1978 New York Yankees season.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The team, who had been trailing the Boston Red Sox of that year by 14 games, turned things around in a late-season push and eventually won a dramatic tie-breaker game against the Red Sox and then the 1978 World Series.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Once the papers went on strike, it is said, the press distractions diminished and the team could focus on playing well.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Kheel served as an unofficial mediator between the two sides and played an important role in the progress of the talks.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] On October 5, the *Post* resumed publication when Rupert Murdoch, its owner and publisher, signed an agreement with the pressmen; however, the *Daily News* and the *Times* were still not being published.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Murdoch's agreement essentially said that the *Post* would abide by whatever terms would be eventually worked out between the unions and the other two papers.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *Post* had been shut down for 56 days.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The *Times* resumed publication along with the *Daily News* on November 6, 1978, after 88 days of non-production.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The newspapers reached an agreement with the unions representing the pressmen.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] The agreement preserved 1,500 existing jobs of the pressmen, but allowed management to reduce staffing through attrition and elimination of some overtime.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] Upon finally reaching agreement, both acknowledged that compromises had been made and said there had been "no victors" in the outcome.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] In particular, it was not a clear victory for management as had happened with the end of the 1975–1976 Washington Post pressmen's strike, a result the unions were striving to avoid in this case.
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] In the short term, the strike cost the newspapers an estimated $150 million in lost advertising and circulation revenue, while workers lost around $60 million in wages not earned (although union strike benefits and state unemployment insurance covered much of that for individual employees).
[src:the-new-york-times/1978-new-york-city-newspaper-strike] In the longer term, the strike coincided with the advent of technological changes that initially took away the pressmen's jobs via newsroom automation and later undermined the economic model of the newspaper industry altogether.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The **2000 Camp David Summit** was a summit meeting at Camp David between United States president Bill Clinton, Israeli prime minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian Authority chairman Yasser Arafat.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The summit took place between 11 and 25 July 2000 and was an effort to end the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The summit ended without an agreement, largely due to irreconcilable differences between Israelis and Palestinians on the status of Jerusalem.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Its failure is considered one of the main triggers of the Second Intifada.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The issues discussed included the establishment of a Palestinian state, the fate of Israeli settlements (illegal under international law), the status of Jerusalem, the question of Palestinian refugees, and potential Israeli control over the airspace and borders of a future Palestinian state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The summit ended after irreconcilable differences over who should have sovereignty over the Temple Mount (which Muslims call *Haram al-Sharif* or Al-Aqsa): Barak insisted on Israeli sovereignty, while Arafat insisted on Palestinian sovereignty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Reports of the outcome of the summit have been described as illustrating the Rashomon effect, in which the multiple witnesses gave contradictory and self-serving interpretations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] After the summit, the Israeli narrative was widely accepted by the American media, which sought to cast Arafat as a villain and that Palestinians did not want peace.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] That narrative led to the decline of the Israeli peace movement.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] U.S. president Bill Clinton announced his invitation to Israeli prime minister Ehud Barak and Yasser Arafat on 5 July 2000, to come to Camp David, Maryland, in order to continue their negotiations on the Middle East peace process.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] There was a hopeful precedent in the 1978 Camp David Accords where President Jimmy Carter was able to broker a peace agreement between Egypt, represented by President Anwar Sadat, and Israel represented by Prime Minister Menachem Begin.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] However, the interim process put in place under Oslo had fulfilled neither Israeli nor Palestinian expectations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] On 11 July, the Camp David 2000 Summit convened, although the Palestinians considered the summit premature.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] They even saw it as a "trap" – meaning either they would be pressured into agreeing to Israeli demands, or they would be blamed for the summit's failure.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Many sources have said the Summit was rushed.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Every day a different meeting, committee and issue.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The summit ended on 25 July, without an agreement being reached.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] At its conclusion, a Trilateral Statement was issued defining the agreed principles to guide future negotiations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The negotiations were based on an all-or-nothing approach, such that "nothing was considered agreed and binding until everything was agreed." The proposals were, for the most part, verbal.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] As no agreement was reached and there is no official written record of the proposals, some ambiguity remains over details of the positions of the parties on specific issues.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinian negotiators indicated they wanted full Palestinian sovereignty over the entire West Bank and the Gaza Strip, although they would consider a one-to-one land swap with Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Their historic position was that Palestinians had already made a territorial compromise with Israel by accepting Israel's right to 78% of "historic Palestine", and accepting their state on the remaining 22% of such land.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] This consensus was expressed by Faisal Husseini when he remarked: "There can be no compromise on the compromise".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] They maintained that Resolution 242 calls for full Israeli withdrawal from these territories, which were captured in the Six-Day War, as part of a final peace settlement.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In the 1993 Oslo Accords the Palestinian negotiators accepted the Green Line borders (1949 armistice lines) for the West Bank but the Israelis rejected this proposal and disputed the Palestinian interpretation of Resolution 242.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel wanted to annex the numerous settlement blocks on the Palestinian side of the Green Line, and were concerned that a complete return to the 1967 borders was dangerous to Israel's security.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinian and Israeli definition of the West Bank differs by approximately 5% land area as the Israeli definition does not include East Jerusalem (71 km2), the territorial waters of the Dead Sea (195 km2) and the area known as No Man's Land (50 km2 near Latrun).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Based on the Israeli definition of the West Bank, Barak offered to form a Palestinian state initially on 73% of the West Bank (that is, 27% less than the Green Line borders) and 100% of the Gaza Strip.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In 10–25 years, the Palestinian state would expand to a maximum of 92% of the West Bank (91 percent of the West Bank and 1 percent from a land swap).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] From the Palestinian perspective this equated to an offer of a Palestinian state on a maximum of 86% of the West Bank.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] According to Robert Wright, Israel would only keep the settlements with large populations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Wright states that all others would be dismantled, with the exception of Kiryat Arba (adjacent to the holy city of Hebron), which would be an Israeli enclave inside the Palestinian state, and would be linked to Israel by a bypass road.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The West Bank would be split in the middle by an Israeli-controlled road from Jerusalem to the Dead Sea, with free passage for Palestinians, although Israel reserved the right to close the road to passage in case of emergency.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In return, Israel would allow the Palestinians to use a highway in the Negev to connect the West Bank with Gaza.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Wright states that in the Israeli proposal, the West Bank and Gaza Strip would be linked by an elevated highway and an elevated railroad running through the Negev, ensuring safe and free passage for Palestinians.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] These would be under the sovereignty of Israel, and Israel reserved the right to close them to passage in case of emergency.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would retain around 9% in the West Bank in exchange for 1% of land within the Green Line.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The land that would be conceded included symbolic and cultural territories such as the Al-Aqsa Mosque, whereas the Israeli land conceded was unspecified.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Additional to territorial concessions, Palestinian airspace would be controlled by Israel under Barak's offer.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinians rejected the Halutza Sand region (78 km2) alongside the Gaza Strip as part of the land swap on the basis that it was of inferior quality to that which they would have to give up in the West Bank.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In the proposed Palestinian state, the Gaza Strip would be discontinuous from the West Bank.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The degree to which the West Bank itself would be discontiguous is disputed.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Noam Chomsky writes that the West Bank would have been divided into three cantons and Palestinian East Jerusalem would have constituted the fourth canton; all four cantons would be separated from one another by Israeli territory.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Other sources also said that the proposed West Bank would be divided into three cantons.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] By contrast, Ehud Barak said the West Bank would only be divided by a wedge of Israeli territory stretching from Maale Adumim to the Jordan River, but would otherwise be continuous.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinians reacted strongly negatively to the proposed cantonization of the West Bank into three blocs, which the Palestinian delegation likened to South African Bantustans, a loaded word that was disputed by the Israeli and American negotiators.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Settlement blocs, bypassed roads and annexed lands would create barriers between Nablus and Jenin with Ramallah.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Ramallah bloc would in turn be divided from Bethlehem and Hebron.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] A separate and smaller bloc would contain Jericho.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Further, the border between West Bank and Jordan would additionally be under Israeli control.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinian Authority would receive pockets of East Jerusalem which would be surrounded entirely by annexed lands in the West Bank.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Arafat insisted on Palestinian sovereignty over the Haram.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] As this deadlock could not be resolved, the summit ended.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Leaders were ill-prepared for the central role the Jerusalem issue in general and the Temple Mount dispute in particular would play in the negotiations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinian position, according to Mahmoud Abbas, at that time Arafat's chief negotiator, was that: "All of East Jerusalem should be returned to Palestinian sovereignty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Jewish Quarter and Western Wall should be placed under Israeli authority, not Israeli sovereignty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israeli negotiators also proposed that the Palestinians be granted administration of, but not sovereignty over, the Muslim and Christian Quarters of the Old City, with the Jewish and Armenian Quarters remaining in Israeli hands.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Palestinians would be granted administrative control over all Islamic and Christian holy sites, and would be allowed to raise the Palestinian flag over them.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] A passage linking northern Jerusalem to Islamic and Christian holy sites would be annexed by the Palestinian state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Israeli team proposed annexing to Israeli Jerusalem settlements within the West Bank beyond the Green Line, such as Ma'ale Adumim, Givat Ze'ev, and Gush Etzion.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel proposed that the Palestinians merge certain outer Arab villages and small cities that had been annexed to Jerusalem just after 1967 (such as Abu Dis, al-Eizariya, 'Anata, A-Ram, and eastern Sawahre) to create the city of Al-Quds, which would serve as the capital of Palestine.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The historically important Arab neighborhoods such as Sheikh Jarrah, Silwan and at-Tur would remain under Israeli sovereignty, while Palestinians would only have civilian autonomy.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinians would exercise civil and administrative autonomy in the outer Arab neighborhoods.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israeli neighborhoods within East Jerusalem would remain under Israeli sovereignty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The holy places in the Old City would enjoy independent religious administration.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In total, Israel demanded that Palestine's territory in East Jerusalem be reduced to eight sections including six small enclaves according to Palestine's delegation to the summit.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Palestinians objected to the lack of sovereignty and to the right of Israel to keep Jewish neighborhoods that it built over the Green Line in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians claimed block the contiguity of the Arab neighborhoods in East Jerusalem.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Due to the first Arab-Israeli war, a significant number of Palestinian Arabs fled or were expelled from their homes inside what is now Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] These refugees numbered approximately 711,000 to 725,000 at the time.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Today, they and their descendants number about four million, comprising about half the Palestinian people.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Since that time, the Palestinians have demanded full implementation of the right of return, meaning that each refugee would be granted the option of returning to his or her home, with property restored, and receive compensation.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israelis asserted that allowing a right of return to Israel proper, rather than to the newly created Palestinian state, would mean an influx of Palestinians that would fundamentally alter the demographics of Israel, jeopardizing Israel's Jewish character and its existence as a whole.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] At Camp David, the Palestinians maintained their traditional demand that the right of return be implemented.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, some of the Palestinian negotiators were willing to privately discuss a limit on the number of refugees who would be allowed to return to Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Palestinians who chose to return to Israel would do so gradually, with Israel absorbing 150,000 refugees every year.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Israeli negotiators denied that Israel was responsible for the refugee problem, and were concerned that any right of return would pose a threat to Israel's Jewish character.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In the Israeli proposal, a maximum of 100,000 refugees would be allowed to return to Israel on the basis of humanitarian considerations or family reunification.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] All other people classified as Palestinian refugees would be settled in their present place of inhabitance, the Palestinian state, or third-party countries.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would help fund their resettlement and absorption.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] An international fund of $30 billion would be set up, which Israel would help contribute to, along with other countries, that would register claims for compensation of property lost by Palestinian refugees and make payments within the limits of its resources.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Israeli negotiators proposed that Israel be allowed to set up radar stations inside the Palestinian state, and be allowed to use its airspace.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel also wanted the right to deploy troops on Palestinian territory in the event of an emergency, and the stationing of an international force in the Jordan Valley.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Palestinian authorities would maintain control of border crossings under temporary Israeli observation.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would maintain a permanent security presence along 15% of the Palestinian-Jordanian border.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel also demanded that the Palestinian state be demilitarized with the exception of its paramilitary security forces, that it would not make alliances without Israeli approval or allow the introduction of foreign forces west of the Jordan River, and that it dismantle terrorist groups.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] One of Israel's strongest demands was that Arafat declare the conflict over, and make no further demands.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel also wanted water resources in the West Bank to be shared by both sides and remain under Israeli management.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] According to Gilead Sher and others, Palestinians made counter-proposals of their own during the negotiations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Just like the Israeli proposals, sources differ on the details.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] On territory, the Palestinian proposal gave Israel either 2.5% (according to Beinart) or 3.1% (according to Emerson and Tocci) of the West Bank.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The proposal demanded any territory in occupied West Bank annexed by Israel be swapped one-to-one with territory inside Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would have to evacuate Kiryat Arba and Hebron.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] A corridor between the West Bank and Gaza Strip was proposed for the movement of people and goods, via a narrow strip of Israeli land.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The corridor would remain under Israeli sovereignty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] On Jerusalem, the Palestinians propose Israeli sovereignty over the Jewish neighborhoods of East Jerusalem and Palestinian sovereignty over the Arab neighborhoods.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In the Old City of Jerusalem, Israel would get the Jewish Quarter and parts of the Armenian Quarter, while Palestine would get the Muslim Quarter and the Christian Quarter.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would get the Western Wall, while Palestinians would get the Temple Mount/Al-Aqsa Mosque.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinians proposed that instead of setting up border checkpoints inside Jerusalem, the border checkpoints should be set around the city.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] This meant Palestinians wishing to enter their own capital city would be treated as crossing an international border (and same with Israelis entering their capital).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] But once inside the city, citizens and traffic would be free to move around.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] If this was not acceptable to Israel, the Palestinian alternate proposal was to have a "hard border" between Israeli and Palestinian parts of Jerusalem.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] On security, the Palestinian proposal allowed for an international military force (including Americans but not including Israelis) to control the Palestinian state's border with Jordan.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The State of Palestine would also coordinate with Israel for the Israeli Airforce to use the Palestinian airspace.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] On refugees, Palestinian insisted on the Right of Return but the proposal would, according to Robert Malley, respect the "preservation of Israel's demographic balance between Jews and Arabs".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Under the Palestinian proposal mechanisms would be created to make it more attractive for refugees to choose to settle any other place beside Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Erekat proposed that the return of Palestinian refugees from Lebanon serve as a "pilot" program to see whether refugees choose to return to Israel or go somewhere else.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In this pilot program, Israel would admit 2,000 refugees per year over a 5-6 year period under the framework of family reunification.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The proposals made to the Palestinians were never put into writing, but told orally to Palestinian negotiators.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] There are conflicting accounts as to what transpired.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The following table summarizes what was finally offered to Palestinians, according to various sources.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Most sources agree, that under Israel's final proposal, the Temple Mount (including Al-Aqsa) would remain under Israeli sovereignty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would also take most of the rest of East Jerusalem, while Palestinians would get some parts too.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel would annex 8% or 13.5% of the West Bank, and would maintain a military of an additional 6–12% of the West Bank for an unspecified period of time (sometimes called a "long term lease").
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] According to some sources, Israel would also retain its settlement blocks in the Gaza Strip.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinian state would not be contiguous and the West Bank would be split into 2 or 3 sections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Finally, Israel would control Palestinian airspace.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] : All 4 Quarters under Israeli sovereignty, but 2 Quarters (Muslim and Christian) offered Palestinian autonomy.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Israel annexes 13% of the West Bank and takes another 6% on "Long term lease".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] All 4 Quarters under Israeli sovereignty, but 2 Quarters (Muslim and Christian) offered autonomy.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In mid-October, Clinton and the parties held a summit in Sharm El Sheikh, resulting in a "Sharm memorandum" with understandings aimed at ending the violence and renewing security cooperation.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] From 18 to 23 December they held negotiations, followed by Clinton's presentation of his "parameters", in a last attempt to achieve peace in the Middle East before his second term ended in January 2001.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Although the official statements stated that both parties had accepted the Clinton Parameters with reservations, these reservations in fact meant that the parties had rejected the parameters on certain essential points.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] On 2 January 2001, the Palestinians put forward their acceptance with some fundamental objections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Barak accepted the parameters with a 20-page letter of reservations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] A Sharm el-Sheikh summit planned for 28 December did not take place.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Ehud Barak was to be defeated by Ariel Sharon in 2001.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Clinton has maintained his disappointment over the failure of the summit to reach a deal.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Shortly after the conclusion of his presidency, Clinton assigned the blame for the failure of the 2000 Camp David Summit squarely on Yasser Arafat and the Palestinians.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] When Arafat called Clinton a great man, Clinton responded, "The hell I am.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] I'm a colossal failure, and you made me one," explaining that Arafat rejected "the best peace deal he was ever going to get" by then Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Which party (parties) should be blamed for the lack of success of the Summit is hotly debated.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In a 2005 book published by Heribert Adam and Kogila Moodley, the authors state "Informed observer blamed all three parties' negotiation strategies for the failure", referring to the Israelis, Palestinians, and Americans.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Nevertheless, after the summit, most of the Israeli and American establishment bought into the Israeli narrative, in which Arafat was portrayed as a villain.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Although it was the question of Jerusalem that dominated the discussions and the Palestinian refugee issue didn't occupy much attention, Israeli leaders instead said that the refugee question led to the collapse of the negotiations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Israeli argument was that the Palestinian right of return meant the end of Israel as a Jewish state, hence it was the Palestinians who didn't want peace.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] This narrative led to the decline of the Israeli peace movement.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Under the Israeli narrative, a Palestinian state in 91% of the West Bank and Gaza was considered "generous" and Palestinians were portrayed as stubborn for not accepting it.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In the Palestinian view, such a proposal was contrary to Resolution 242.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In their view, the Palestinians had already compromised by conceding 78% of historic Palestine to Israel and accepting a Palestinian state in only 22% of the land and thus should not be expected to concede even more land to Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Palestinians also saw Israeli proposals to control Palestinian airspace, borders and natural resources as an attempt to maintain the occupation indefinitely.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Most of the Israeli and American criticism for the failure of the 2000 Camp David Summit was leveled at Arafat.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Ehud Barak portrays Arafat's behavior at Camp David as a "performance geared to exact as many Israeli concessions as possible without ever seriously intending to reach a peace settlement or sign an "end to the conflict".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Arafat was also accused of scuttling the talks by Nabil Amr, a former minister in the Palestinian Authority.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In *My Life*, Clinton wrote that Arafat once complimented Clinton by telling him, "You are a great man." Clinton responded, "I am not a great man.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Dennis Ross, the US Middle East envoy and a key negotiator at the summit, summarized his perspectives in his book *The Missing Peace*.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] During a lecture in Australia, Ross suggested that the reason for the failure was Arafat's unwillingness to sign a final deal with Israel that would close the door on any of the Palestinians' maximum demands, particularly the right of return.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Ross claimed that what Arafat really wanted was "a one-state solution.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Not independent, adjacent Israeli and Palestinian states, but a single Arab state encompassing all of Historic Palestine".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] In his book, *The Oslo Syndrome*, Harvard Medical School professor of psychiatry and historian Kenneth Levin summarized the failure of the 2000 Camp David Summit in this manner: "despite the dimensions of the Israeli offer and intense pressure from President Clinton, Arafat demurred.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Alan Dershowitz, an Israel advocate and law professor at Harvard University, said that the failure of the negotiations was due to "the refusal of the Palestinians and Arafat to give up the right of return.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Robert Malley, part of the Clinton administration and present at the summit, wrote to dispel three "myths" regarding the summit's failure.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] First myth, Malley says, was "Camp David was an ideal test of Mr.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Malley recalls that Arafat didn't think that Israeli and Palestinian diplomats had sufficiently narrowed issues in preparation for the summit and that the Summit happened at a "low point" in the relations between Arafat and Barak.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The second myth was "Israel's offer met most if not all of the Palestinians' legitimate aspirations".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] According to Malley, Arafat was told that Israel would not only retain sovereignty over some Arab neighborhoods of Jerusalem, but Haram al Sharif too, and Arafat was also asked to accept an unfavorable 9-to-1 ratio in land swaps.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The third myth was that "The Palestinians made no concession of their own".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Malley pointed out that the Palestinians starting position was at the 1967 borders, but they were ready to give up Jewish neighborhoods in East Jerusalem, and parts of the West Bank with Israeli settlements.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Further, the Palestinians were willing to implement the right of return in a way that guaranteed Israel's demographic interests.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] He argues that Arafat was far more compromising in his negotiations with Israel than Anwar el-Sadat or King Hussein of Jordan had been when they negotiated with Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Clayton Swisher wrote a rebuttal to Clinton and Ross's accounts about the causes for the breakdown of the Camp David Summit in his 2004 book, *The Truth About Camp David*.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Swisher, the Director of Programs at the Middle East Institute, concluded that the Israelis and the Americans were at least as guilty as the Palestinians for the collapse.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Norman Finkelstein published an article in the winter 2007 issue of *Journal of Palestine Studies,* excerpting from his longer essay called *Subordinating Palestinian Rights to Israeli "Needs"*.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The abstract for the article states: "In particular, it examines the assumptions informing Ross’s account of what happened during the negotiations and why, and the distortions that spring from these assumptions.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Israeli group Gush Shalom stated that "the offer is a pretense of generosity for the benefit of the media", and included detailed maps of what the offer specifically entailed.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] The Palestinian public was supportive of Arafat's role in the negotiations.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] After the summit, Arafat's approval rating increased seven percentage points from 39 to 46%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Overall, 68% of the Palestinian public thought Arafat's positions on a final agreement at Camp David were just right and 14% thought Arafat compromised too much while only 6% thought Arafat had not compromised enough.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] However, when asked about specific positions Arafat had taken during the negotiations, Palestinians were more critical.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Barak did not fare as well in public opinion polls.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] Only 25% of the Israeli public thought his positions on Camp David were just right as opposed to 58% of the public that thought Barak compromised too much.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-camp-david-summit] A majority of Israelis were opposed to Barak's position on every issue discussed at Camp David except for security.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 7, 2000.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican ticket of Texas governor George W.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and former secretary of defense Dick Cheney narrowly defeated the Democratic ticket of incumbent vice president Al Gore and Connecticut junior senator Joe Lieberman.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was the fourth of five U.S. presidential elections, and the first since 1888 in which the winning candidate lost the popular vote, and is considered one of the closest U.S. presidential elections in history, with long-standing controversy about the result.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Democratic president Bill Clinton was ineligible to seek a third term because of term limits established by the 22nd Amendment.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent vice president Gore easily secured the Democratic nomination, defeating former New Jersey senator Bill Bradley in the primaries.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He selected Connecticut senator Joe Lieberman as his running mate.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush—the eldest son of former president George H.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush—was seen as the early favorite for the Republican nomination, and after a contentious primary battle with Arizona senator John McCain and others, he secured the nomination by Super Tuesday.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He selected former secretary of defense Dick Cheney as his running mate.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both major-party candidates focused primarily on domestic issues, such as the budget, tax relief, and reforms for federal social insurance programs, although foreign policy was not ignored.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Due to President Clinton's sex scandal with Monica Lewinsky and subsequent impeachment, Gore avoided campaigning with Clinton.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Republicans denounced Clinton's indiscretions, while Gore criticized Bush's lack of experience.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On election night, it was unclear who had won, with the electoral votes of the state of Florida still undecided.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It took over a month to resolve the issue: recounts and ensuing litigation were finally settled by the highly controversial U.S.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore*, which ensured that Florida's electoral votes went to Bush, tipping the election in his favor.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush carried Florida by only 537 votes out of 5.96 million cast in the state (a margin of 0.009%).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ultimately, Bush won 271 electoral votes, one vote more than the 270 required to win, while Gore won the popular vote by 543,895 votes (a margin of 0.52% of all votes cast).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush flipped 11 states that had voted Democratic in 1996: Arkansas, Arizona, Florida, Kentucky, Louisiana, Missouri, Nevada, New Hampshire, Ohio, Tennessee, and West Virginia.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite Gore's loss, this election marked the first time since 1948 that the Democratic Party won the popular vote in three consecutive elections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] President Bill Clinton, a Democrat and former governor of Arkansas, was ineligible to seek reelection to a third term due to the Twenty-second Amendment; in accordance with Section 1 of the Twentieth Amendment, his term expired at noon Eastern Standard Time on January 20, 2001.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush became the early front-runner, acquiring unprecedented funding and a broad base of leadership support based on his governorship of Texas, the Bush family's name recognition, and connections in American politics.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former cabinet member George Shultz played an important early role in securing establishment Republican support for Bush.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In April 1998, he invited Bush to discuss policy issues with experts including Michael Boskin, John Taylor, and Condoleezza Rice, who later became his secretary of state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The group, which was "looking for a candidate for 2000 with good political instincts, someone they could work with", was impressed, and Shultz encouraged him to enter the race.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Several aspirants withdrew before the Iowa caucuses because they did not secure funding and endorsements sufficient to remain competitive with Bush.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These included Elizabeth Dole, Dan Quayle, Lamar Alexander, and Bob Smith.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Pat Buchanan dropped out to run for the Reform Party nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] That left Bush, John McCain, Alan Keyes, Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer, and Orrin Hatch as the only candidates still in the race.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On January 24, Bush won the Iowa caucuses with 41% of the vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Forbes came in second with 30% of the vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Keyes received 14%, Bauer 9%, McCain 5%, and Hatch 1%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Two days later, Hatch dropped out and endorsed Bush.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The national media portrayed Bush as the establishment candidate.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the support of many moderate Republicans and independents, McCain portrayed himself as a crusading insurgent who focused on campaign reform.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On February 1, McCain, who had skipped the caucuses in order to divert resources toward New Hampshire and South Carolina, won a surprising 49–30% victory over Bush in the New Hampshire primary.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bauer subsequently dropped out, followed by Forbes, who had won no primaries after spending $32 million of his own money on his campaign.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the South Carolina primary, Bush soundly defeated McCain.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some McCain supporters accused the Bush campaign of mudslinging and negative campaigning, citing push polls that implied that McCain's adopted Bangladeshi-born daughter was an African-American child he fathered out of wedlock.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain's loss in South Carolina damaged his campaign, but he won both Michigan and his home state of Arizona on February 22.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The primary campaigns impacted the South Carolina State House, where a controversy about the Confederate flag flying over the capitol dome prompted the state legislature to move the flag to a less prominent position at a Civil War memorial on the capitol grounds.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most GOP candidates said the issue should be left to South Carolina voters, but McCain later recanted and said the flag should be removed.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain criticized Bush for speaking at and accepting the endorsement of Bob Jones University despite its policy banning interracial dating, actions for which Bush subsequently apologized.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On February 28, McCain also referred to Jerry Falwell and televangelist Pat Robertson as "agents of intolerance," a term from which he distanced himself during his 2008 bid.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He lost Virginia to Bush on February 29.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On Super Tuesday, March 7, Bush won New York, Ohio, Georgia, Missouri, California, Maryland, and Maine.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain won Rhode Island, Vermont, Connecticut, and Massachusetts but dropped out of the race.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain became the Republican presidential nominee 8 years later, but lost the general election to Barack Obama.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush took the majority of the remaining contests and won the Republican nomination on March 14, winning his home state of Texas and his brother Jeb's home state of Florida, among others.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Bush accepted the nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush asked former secretary of defense Dick Cheney to head up a team to help select a running mate for him, but ultimately chose Cheney himself as the vice presidential nominee.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Constitution does not specifically disallow a president and a vice president from the same state, it prohibits electors from casting both of their votes for persons from their own state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Accordingly, Cheney—who had been a resident of Texas for nearly 10 years—changed his voting registration back to Wyoming.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Had Cheney not done this, either he or Bush would have forfeited his electoral votes from Texas.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Vice President Al Gore was a consistent front-runner for the nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Other prominent Democrats mentioned as possible contenders included Bob Kerrey, Missouri Representative Dick Gephardt, Minnesota Senator Paul Wellstone, and actor and director Warren Beatty.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of these, only Wellstone formed an exploratory committee.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Bill Bradley positioned himself as the alternative to Gore, who was a founding member of the centrist Democratic Leadership Council.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore easily defeated Bradley in the primaries, largely because of support from the Democratic Party establishment and Bradley's poor showing in the Iowa caucus, where Gore successfully painted Bradley as aloof and indifferent to the plight of farmers.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The closest Bradley came to a victory was his 50–46 loss to Gore in the New Hampshire primary.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 14, Gore clinched the Democratic nomination.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] None of Bradley's delegates were allowed to vote for him, so Gore won the nomination unanimously at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Connecticut Senator Joe Lieberman was nominated for vice president by voice vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lieberman became the first Jewish American ever to be chosen for this position by a major party.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore chose Lieberman over five other finalists: Senators Evan Bayh, John Edwards, and John Kerry, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, and New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The nomination went to Pat Buchanan and running mate Ezola Foster from California over the objections of party founder Ross Perot and despite a rump convention nomination of John Hagelin by the Perot faction.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the end, the Federal Election Commission sided with Buchanan, and that ticket appeared on 49 of 51 possible ballots.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Real estate magnate Donald Trump also sought the Reform Party nomination but soon withdrew from the race.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He ran three more times as the Republican nominee and was elected the 45th president in 2016, lost reelection in 2020, and was elected the 47th president in 2024.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Greens/Green Party USA, a then-recognized national party organization, later endorsed Nader for president and he appeared on the ballots of 43 states and Washington, D.C.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Libertarian Party's National Nominating Convention nominated Harry Browne from Tennessee and Art Olivier from California for president and vice president.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Browne was nominated on the first ballot and Olivier received the vice presidential nomination on the second ballot.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Browne appeared on every state ballot except Arizona's, due to a dispute between the Libertarian Party of Arizona (which instead nominated L.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Neil Smith) and the national Libertarian Party.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Constitution Party nominated Howard Phillips from Virginia for a third time and Curtis Frazier from Missouri.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Natural Law Party held its national convention in Arlington County, Virginia, on August 31–September 2, unanimously nominating a ticket of Hagelin/Goldhaber without a roll-call vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party was on 38 of the 51 ballots nationally.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The US economy was enjoying record prosperity in the late 1990s.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although the campaign focused mainly on domestic issues, such as the projected budget surplus, proposed reforms of Social Security and Medicare, health care, and competing plans for tax relief, foreign policy was a prominent issue.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush criticized the Clinton administration's policies in Somalia, where 18 Americans died in 1993 intervening among warring factions, and in the Balkans, where United States troops performed a variety of functions.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] "I don't think our troops ought to be used for what's called nation-building", Bush said in the second presidential debate.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush also pledged to bridge partisan gaps, claiming the atmosphere in Washington stood in the way of progress on necessary reforms.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore, meanwhile, questioned Bush's fitness for the job, pointing to gaffes Bush made in interviews and speeches and suggesting he lacked the necessary experience to be president.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bill Clinton's impeachment and the sex scandal that led up to it cast a shadow on the campaign.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Republicans strongly denounced the Clinton scandals, and Bush made a promise to restore "honor and dignity" to the White House a centerpiece of his campaign.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore studiously avoided the Clinton scandals, as did Lieberman, even though Lieberman had been the first Democratic senator to denounce Clinton's misbehavior.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some observers theorized that Gore chose Lieberman in an attempt to separate himself from Clinton's past misdeeds and help blunt the GOP's attempts to link him to his boss.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Others pointed to the passionate kiss Gore gave his wife during the Democratic Convention as a signal that despite the allegations against Clinton, Gore himself was a faithful husband.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore avoided appearing with Clinton, who was shunted to low-visibility appearances in areas where he was popular.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Experts have argued that this could have cost Gore votes from some of Clinton's core supporters.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ralph Nader was the most successful of the third-party candidates.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His campaign was marked by a traveling tour of large "super-rallies" held in sports arenas like Madison Square Garden, with retired talk show host Phil Donahue as master of ceremonies.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the other side, the Republican Leadership Council ran pro-Nader ads in a few states in an effort to split the liberal vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nader said his campaign's objective was to pass the 5-percent threshold so his Green Party would be eligible for matching funds in future races.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Vice-presidential candidates Cheney and Lieberman campaigned aggressively.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both camps made numerous campaign stops nationwide, often just missing each other, such as when Cheney, Hadassah Lieberman, and Tipper Gore attended Chicago's Taste of Polonia over Labor Day Weekend.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the 1996 presidential election, the Commission on Presidential Debates set new candidate selection criteria.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The new criteria required third-party candidates to poll at least 15% of the vote in national polls in order to take part in the CPD-sponsored presidential debates.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nader was blocked from attending a closed-circuit screening of the first debate despite having a ticket, and barred from attending an interview near the site of the third debate (Washington University in St.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Louis) despite having a "perimeter pass".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nader later sued the CPD for its role in the former incident.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A settlement was reached that included an apology to him.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] ★Although the Libertarian Party had ballot access in all fifty United States plus D.C., Browne's name only appeared on the ballot in forty-nine United States plus D.C.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Libertarian Party of Arizona opted to place L.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Neil Smith on the ballot in Browne's place.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] When adding Smith's 5,775 Arizona votes to Browne's 384,431 votes nationwide, that brings the total presidential votes cast for the Libertarian Party in 2000 to 390,206.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On election night, it was unclear who had won, with Florida's electoral votes still undecided.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The returns showed that Bush won Florida by such a close margin that state law required a recount.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A month-long series of legal battles led to the highly controversial 5–4 U.S.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore*, which ended the recount with Bush winning Florida by 537 votes, a margin of 0.009%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Florida recount and subsequent litigation resulted in major post-election controversy, with some analysis suggesting that limited county-based recounts would have confirmed a Bush victory whereas a statewide recount would have given the state to Gore.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Post-election analysis found that Palm Beach County's butterfly ballot misdirected over 2,000 votes from Gore to third-party candidate Pat Buchanan, tipping Florida—and the election—to Bush.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] With the exceptions of Florida and Gore's home state of Tennessee, Bush carried the Southern states by comfortable margins, including Clinton's home state of Arkansas, and also won Ohio, Indiana, most of the rural Midwestern farming states, most of the Rocky Mountain states, and Alaska.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore balanced Bush by sweeping the Northeastern United States (with the exception of New Hampshire, which Bush won narrowly), the Pacific Coast states, Hawaii, New Mexico, and most of the Upper Midwest.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the only presidential election since 1988 where the Republican candidate carried any of the six New England states.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As the night wore on, the returns in a handful of small-to-medium-sized states, including Iowa, Oregon and New Mexico (Gore by 355 votes) were extremely close, but the election came down to Florida.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As the final national results were tallied the following morning, Bush had clearly won 246 electoral votes and Gore 249, with 270 needed to win.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Two smaller states—Wisconsin (11 electoral votes) and Oregon (7)—were still too close to call, but Florida's 25 electoral votes would be decisive regardless of their results.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election's outcome was not known for more than a month after voting ended because of the time required to count and recount Florida's ballots.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] EST on November 7, just before the polls closed in the largely Republican Florida panhandle, which is in the Central time zone, all major television news networks (CNN, NBC, FOX, CBS, and ABC) declared that Gore had won Florida.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They based this prediction substantially on exit polls.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] But in the vote, Bush began to take a wide lead early in Florida, and by 10 p.m.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] EST, the networks had retracted their predictions and placed Florida back in the "undecided" column.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At approximately 2:30 a.m. on November 8, with 85% of the vote counted in Florida and Bush leading Gore by more than 100,000 votes, the networks declared that Bush had carried Florida and therefore been elected president.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] But most of the remaining votes to be counted in Florida were in three heavily Democratic counties—Broward, Miami-Dade, and Palm Beach—and as their votes were reported Gore began to gain on Bush.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By 4:30 a.m., after all votes were counted, Gore had narrowed Bush's margin to under 2,000 votes, and the networks retracted their declarations that Bush had won Florida and the presidency.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore, who had privately conceded the election to Bush, withdrew his concession.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The final result in Florida was slim enough to require a mandatory recount (by machine) under state law; Bush's lead dwindled to just over 300 votes when it was completed the day after the election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On November 8, Florida Division of Elections staff prepared a press release for Florida Secretary of State Katherine Harris that said overseas ballots must be "postmarked or signed and dated" by Election Day.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A count of the overseas ballots later boosted Bush's margin to 930 votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Most of the post-electoral controversy revolved around Gore's request for hand recounts in four counties (Broward, Miami-Dade, Palm Beach, and Volusia), as provided under Florida state law.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Harris, who also co-chaired Bush's Florida campaign, announced she would reject any revised totals from those counties if they were not turned in by 5 p.m. on November 14, the statutory deadline for amended returns.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Florida Supreme Court extended the deadline to November 26, a decision later vacated by the U.S.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Miami-Dade eventually halted its recount and resubmitted its original total to the state canvassing board, while Palm Beach County failed to meet the extended deadline, turning in its completed recount results at 7 p.m., which Harris rejected.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On November 26, the state canvassing board certified Bush as the winner of Florida's electors by 537 votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore formally contested the certified results.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A state court decision overruling Gore was reversed by the Florida Supreme Court, which ordered a recount of over 70,000 ballots previously rejected as undervotes by machine counters.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Supreme Court halted that order the next day, with Justice Scalia issuing a concurring opinion that "the counting of votes that are of questionable legality does in my view threaten irreparable harm to petitioner" (Bush).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On December 12, the Supreme Court in Bush v.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] With only two hours remaining until the December 12 deadline, the Supreme Court's order effectively ended the recount, and the previously certified total held.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even if the Supreme Court had decided differently in *Bush v.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore*, the Florida Legislature had been meeting in Special Session since December 8 with the purpose of selecting of a slate of electors on December 12 should the dispute still be ongoing.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Had the recount gone forward, it would have awarded those electors to Bush, based on the state-certified vote, and Gore's likely last recourse would have been to contest the electors in the United States Congress.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The electors would then have been rejected only if both houses agreed to do so.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] From the beginning of the controversy, politicians, litigants, and the press focused exclusively on undervotes, in particular incompletely punched hanging chads.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Undervotes were the subject of much media coverage, most of the lawsuits, and the Florida Supreme Court ruling.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the election, recounts by various U.S. news media organizations continued to focus on undervotes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Results of reviews of these ballots indicated that Bush would have won if certain recounting methods had been used (including the one Gore favored at the time of the Supreme Court decision), but that Gore might have won under other standards and scenarios.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Later, a larger consortium of news organizations, including *USA Today*, *The Miami Herald*, Knight Ridder, *The Tampa Tribune*, and five other newspapers conducted a full recount of all machine-rejected ballots, including both undervotes and overvotes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It found that Bush won under stricter standards and Gore won under looser standards.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Finally, the National Opinion Research Center at the University of Chicago, sponsored by a consortium of major U.S. news organizations, conducted the Florida Ballot Project, a comprehensive review of ballots collected from the entire state, not just the disputed counties that were recounted.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Based on the NORC review, the media group concluded that if the disputes over the validity of all the ballots in question had been consistently resolved and any uniform standard applied, Gore would have won Florida by 60 to 171 votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The standards chosen for the NORC study ranged from a "most restrictive" standard to a "most inclusive" standard.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An analysis of the NORC data by University of Pennsylvania researcher Steven F.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Freeman and journalist Joel Bleifuss concluded that, no matter the standard used, after a recount of all uncounted votes, Gore would have been the victor.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to factcheck.org, "Nobody can say for sure who might have won.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] They also concluded that had a full recount of all undervotes and overvotes taken place, Gore would have won, though his legal team never pursued such an option.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Though Gore came in second in the electoral vote, he received 543,895 more popular votes than Bush, making him the first person since Grover Cleveland in 1888 to win the popular vote but lose in the Electoral College.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore failed to win the popular vote in his home state, Tennessee, which both he and his father had represented in the Senate, making him the first major-party presidential candidate to have lost his home state since George McGovern lost South Dakota in 1972.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, Gore lost West Virginia, a state that had voted Republican only once in the previous six presidential elections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1948 that Democrats won the popular vote in three consecutive elections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is one of only four U.S. presidential elections in which the winner did not carry any of the three Rust Belt states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin; the others were 2004, 1916 and 1884.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 2000 election was also a rare instance in which the party controlling the White House lost a presidential election when the U.S. economy was not in a recession, the 1968 election being the most recent one.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It is also the only election since 1968 where the popular vote was decided by under 1%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Before the election, the possibility that different candidates would win the popular vote and the Electoral College had been noted, but usually with the expectation of Gore winning the Electoral College and Bush the popular vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The idea that Bush could win the Electoral College and Gore the popular vote was not considered likely.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1928 when a non-incumbent Republican candidate won West Virginia.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Electoral College results were the closest since 1876, making this election the second-closest Electoral College result in history and the third-closest popular vote victory.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gore's 266 electoral votes are the highest for a losing nominee.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 537-vote margin in Florida is the closest for a tipping point state in history.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush was the first winning Republican since William McKinley to win with under 300 electoral votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He was also the first son of a former president to be elected president himself since John Quincy Adams in 1824.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush was the first Republican in American history to win the presidency without carrying Vermont, Illinois, or New Mexico, as well as the second Republican to win the presidency without carrying California after James A.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Garfield in 1880, and Pennsylvania, Maine, Michigan, and Connecticut after Richard Nixon in 1968, as well as the first winning Republican not to receive any electoral votes from California as Garfield received one electoral vote in 1880.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush was the first Republican to win without New Jersey or Delaware since 1888.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2024, Bush is the last Republican nominee to win New Hampshire.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This marked the first time since Iowa entered the union in 1846 in which the state voted for a Democratic presidential candidate in four elections in a row and the last time until 2020 that Iowa did not vote for the overall winner.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush is the second Republican to win the presidency without Iowa (his father was the first, in 1988).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were only two counties in the nation that had voted Republican in 1996 and flipped to the Democratic column in 2000: Charles County, Maryland, and Orange County, Florida, both rapidly diversifying counties, neither of which has voted Republican since.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the last time until 2024 in which an incumbent vice president ran for president.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the last time a Republican received any electoral votes from the Northeast until 2016.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This and the following election were the only ones since 1980 in which the winner received fewer than 300 electoral votes (less than 55% of the total).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush is the most recent candidate with gubernatorial experience to win the presidency.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the most recent election in which both major-party nominees were under age 60.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] †Maine and Nebraska each allow for their electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In both states, two electoral votes are awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote is awarded to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The votes for each candidate are only singly counted in the column totals.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] After Florida was decided and Gore conceded, Texas Governor George W.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush became the president-elect and began forming his transition committee.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In a speech on December 13, in the Texas House of Representatives chamber, Bush said he was reaching across party lines to bridge a divided America, saying, "the President of the United States is the President of every single American, of every race, and every background".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] During the transition period, Clinton staffers, upset by Gore's loss, reportedly vandalized White House furnishings, including removing the W keys from computer keyboards and stealing items, including several antique doorknobs.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Approximately $15,000 in damage was reported.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] On January 6, 2001, a joint session of Congress met to count the electoral votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Twenty members of the House of Representatives, most of them members of the all-Democratic Congressional Black Caucus, rose one by one to file objections to the electoral votes of Florida.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] But pursuant to the Electoral Count Act, any such objection had to be sponsored by both a representative and a senator.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] No senator co-sponsored these objections, deferring to the Supreme Court's ruling.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Therefore, Gore, who presided in his capacity as President of the Senate, ruled each of these objections out of order.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Subsequently, Congress counted the electoral votes from all 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore was the last incumbent vice president until Kamala Harris to certify their opponent's Electoral College victory in a presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush took the oath of office on January 20, 2001.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore has not, as of 2024, considered another presidential run, endorsing Howard Dean's candidacy during the 2004 Democratic primary and remaining neutral in the Democratic primaries of 2008, 2016 and 2020.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The first independent recount of undervotes was conducted by the *Miami Herald* and *USA Today*.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The commission found that under most scenarios for completion of the initiated recounts, Bush would have won the election, but Gore would have won using the most generous standards for undervotes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Ultimately, a media consortium—comprising *The New York Times*, *The Washington Post*, *The Wall Street Journal*, Tribune Co.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] (parent of the *Los Angeles Times*), Associated Press, CNN, *The Palm Beach Post* and the *St.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Their goal was to determine the reliability and accuracy of the systems used for the voting process.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Such a statewide review including all uncounted votes was a tangible possibility, as Leon County Circuit Court Judge Terry Lewis, whom the Florida Supreme Court had assigned to oversee the statewide recount, had scheduled a hearing for December 13 (mooted by the U.S.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Supreme Court's final ruling on the 12th) to consider the question of including overvotes as well as undervotes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Subsequent statements by Lewis and internal court documents support the likelihood of including overvotes in the recount.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Florida State University professor of public policy Lance deHaven-Smith observed that, even considering only undervotes, "under any of the five most reasonable interpretations of the Florida Supreme Court ruling, Gore does, in fact, more than make up the deficit".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting's analysis of the NORC study and media coverage of it supports these interpretations and criticizes the coverage of the study by media outlets such as *The New York Times* and the other media consortium members.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Further, according to sociologists Christopher Uggen and Jeff Manza, the 2000 election might have gone to Gore if the disenfranchised population of Florida had voted.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Florida law disenfranchises convicted felons, requiring individual applications to regain suffrage.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In a 2002 *American Sociological Review* article, Uggen and Manza found that the released felon vote could have altered the outcome of seven senatorial races between 1978 and 2000, and the 2000 presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Because the 2000 presidential election was so close in Florida, the federal government and state governments pushed for election reform to be prepared by the 2004 presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This resulted in an unusual number of overvotes (voting for more candidates than is allowed) and undervotes (voting for fewer than the minimum candidates, including none at all).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Many undervotes were caused by voter error, unmaintained punch card voting booths, or errors having to do merely with the characteristics of punch card ballots (resulting in hanging, dimpled, or pregnant chads).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Post-election analyses of Florida voting data found higher rates of ballot spoilage in Florida counties with larger numbers of African Americans, especially in Duval County, with its "caterpillar ballot", in which the presidential section stretched across multiple pages.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A proposed solution to these problems was the installation of modern electronic voting machines.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2000 presidential election spurred the debate about election and voting reform but did not end it.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In the aftermath of the election, the Help America Vote Act (HAVA) was passed to help states upgrade their election technology in the hopes of preventing similar problems in future elections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] But the electronic voting systems that many states purchased to comply with HAVA actually caused problems in the 2004 presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The Voter News Service's reputation was damaged by its treatment of Florida's presidential vote in 2000.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Breaking its own guidelines, VNS called the state as a win for Gore 12 minutes before polls closed in the Florida Panhandle.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Although most of the state is in the Eastern Time Zone, counties in the Panhandle, in the Central Time Zone, had not yet closed their polls.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Discrepancies between the results of exit polls and the actual vote count caused the VNS to change its call twice, first from Gore to Bush and then to "too close to call." Due in part to this (and other polling inaccuracies) the VNS was disbanded in 2003.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to Bush adviser Karl Rove, exit polls early in the afternoon on election day showed Gore winning by three percentage points, but when the networks called the state for Gore, Bush led by about 75,000 votes in raw tallies from the Florida Secretary of State.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Charges of media bias were leveled against the networks by Republicans, who claimed that the networks called states more quickly for Al Gore than for George W.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Congress held hearings on this matter, at which the networks claimed to have no intentional bias in their election night reporting.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The early call of Florida for Gore has been alleged to have cost Bush several close states, including Iowa, New Mexico, Oregon, and Wisconsin.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In each of these states, Gore won by less than 10,000 votes, and the polls closed after the networks called Florida for Gore.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Lott's survey assumed that the turnout in the western Panhandle counties, which was 65%, would have equaled the statewide average of 68% if the state had not been called for Gore while the polls were open.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] But the smaller turnout in the Panhandle has been attributed to the surge in the black vote elsewhere in Florida to 16% of the total from 10% of the total in 1996.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Research by Henry Brady and David Collier strongly disputes Lott's findings.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Brady and Collier sharply criticize Lott's methodology and claim that when all relevant factors are accounted for, the early call likely cost Bush only between 28 and 56 votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Many Gore supporters claimed that Green Party nominee Ralph Nader acted as a spoiler in the election, under the presumption that Nader voters would have voted for Gore had Nader not been in the race.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Nader received 2.74% of the popular vote nationwide, including 97,000 votes in Florida (by comparison, there were 111,251 overvotes) and 22,000 in New Hampshire, where Bush beat Gore by 7,000 votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Winning either state would have made Gore president.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Dan Perkins agreed and said that the margin in Florida was small enough that Democrats could blame any number of third-party candidates for the defeat, including Workers World Party candidate Monica Moorehead, who received 1,500 votes.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Nader's reputation was hurt by this perception, which may have hindered his goals as an activist.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] For example, *Mother Jones* wrote about the so-called "rank-and-file liberals" who saw Nader negatively after the election and pointed out that Public Citizen, the organization Nader founded in 1971, suffered a drop in contributions.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] *Mother Jones* also cited a Public Citizen letter sent out to people interested in Nader's relation with the organization at that time, with the disclaimer: "Although Ralph Nader was our founder, he has not held an official position in the organization since 1980 and does not serve on the board.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Public Citizen—and the other groups that Mr.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In their 2007 book *The Nightly News Nightmare: Network Television's Coverage of US Presidential Elections, 1988–2004*, professors Stephen J.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Robert Lichter said that most media outlets influenced the outcome of the election through the use of horse race journalism.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Some liberal supporters of Al Gore argued that the media had a bias against Gore and in favor of Bush.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] A number of subsequent articles have characterized the election in 2000, and the Supreme Court's decision in *Bush v.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore*, as damaging the reputation of the Supreme Court, increasing the view of judges as partisan, and decreasing Americans' trust in the integrity of elections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The number of lawsuits brought over election issues more than doubled following the 2000 election cycle, an increase Richard L.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Hasen of UC Irvine School of Law attributes to the "Florida fiasco".
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In 2012, Westgate Resorts owner David A.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Siegel admitted to surveying 8,000 Westgate employees nationwide and ensuring that those who supported Gore would not vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Siegel, whose corporation was also based in Florida, acknowledged that his actions may have illegally blocked votes for Gore and ensured that Bush won the state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2000 presidential election saw an increase in the urban-rural political divide and caused regional realignments that would evolve in the 21st century.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush made major gains in most counties, particularly outside urban areas.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The District of Columbia and every state except Maryland shifted rightward from the 1996 presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The next time such a uniform shift occurred was in the 2024 presidential election, when every state, every Congressional District with electoral votes except Nebraska's 2nd congressional district, and D.C. shifted rightward from the 2020 presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Except in 2008, no major-party ticket has won fewer than 200 electoral votes in any 21st-century election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush's 426 electoral votes and 7.7% popular-vote margin in 1988.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore's popular-vote margin of 0.5% remains the lowest of any presidential election since 2000.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The demographic swings in the 2000 presidential election foreshadowed realignments that continued to evolve.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] It was the first election in which whites without college degrees voted significantly more Republican than college-educated whites, though income was still a key dividing line.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In 2016, education replaced income as the political dividing line among whites.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] By 2024, education had replaced income among all voters except Black voters.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Non-college whites swung toward Bush, which fueled his gains in the South.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] According to Split Ticket estimates, Bush won non-college whites by 17 points and college-educated whites by 9 points, winning whites as a whole by 13 points.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush also made large gains with Hispanic voters and did even better among them in 2004.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] For example, Bush gained in Miami-Dade County, Florida, helping him win the state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore did well with African American voters, though it was not enough to win any Southern state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] He also marginally improved among white women with college degrees, which foreshadowed increased Democratic strength in that demographic.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2000 presidential election marked the permanent realignment of most of the Southern United States to the Republican Party at the presidential level.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In addition to his home state of Tennessee, Gore lost every Southern state despite the closeness of the electoral vote and popular vote.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore's performance in the South was similar to that of Michael Dukakis in 1988, even as Gore won the popular vote by 0.5% and Dukakis lost it by 7.7%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] No Democratic presidential nominee has won Alaska, Idaho, Utah, Wyoming, North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska (excluding Nebraska's 2nd congressional district), Kansas, or Oklahoma since 1964.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] None has won South Carolina, Alabama, Mississippi, or Texas since 1976.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] None has won Louisiana, Arkansas, Missouri, Tennessee, Kentucky, or West Virginia since 1996.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore suffered particularly steep losses in Appalachia and the Upper South, which foreshadowed Democrats' 21st-century performance in those regions.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] For example, Dukakis won West Virginia in 1988, but Gore lost it, and it became one of the nation's most reliably Republican states thereafter.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Virginia has supported the Democratic nominee in every presidential election since 2008.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] But every winning Republican presidential ticket has carried all the other ten former Confederate states in every 21st-century presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In 2008, Barack Obama won Virginia, North Carolina, and Florida, and in 2012 he won Virginia and Florida.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] In 2020, Joe Biden won Virginia and Georgia, the only 21st-century Democratic presidential nominee to win a Deep South state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore held up well in the Midwest, losing only two states Bill Clinton won in 1996, Ohio (by 3.51%) and Missouri (by 3.34%).
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] He won Wisconsin by 0.22% and Iowa by 0.32%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore's performance in the Midwest later inspired the phrase "blue wall", referring to states that voted for Democratic presidential nominees from 1992 to 2012.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2000 presidential election also marked the realignment of much of the Western United States, particularly the West Coast, toward the Democratic Party.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The West Coast was competitive at the time, with Gore winning California by 12% and Washington by 5.5%.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Gore narrowly won Oregon (by 0.44%) and New Mexico (by 0.06%), the latter of which was actually closer in raw votes than Florida.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] California was believed to be competitive at the time and Bush campaigned there, but Gore won it by double digits.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Democratic nominees have won Oregon in all 21st-century presidential elections.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush won Colorado and New Mexico in 2004, the last time a Republican presidential nominee has won either state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This election was the last time Nevada voted for the popular-vote loser.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] It has voted for the popular-vote winner in all subsequent presidential elections, the longest streak of any U.S. state.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Arizona stayed Republican except in 2020, when it narrowly voted for Joe Biden.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] The 2000 presidential election was much less of a realignment in the Northeastern United States.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] Bush won New Hampshire by 1.27% and lost all other northeastern states.
[src:the-new-york-times/2000-united-states-presidential-election-p03] This was the last time any New England state voted Republican, although Donald Trump won Maine's 2nd congressional district in all three of his runs.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* was founded as the conservative *New-York Daily Times* in 1851, and came to national recognition in the 1870s with its aggressive coverage of corrupt politician Boss Tweed.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Following the Panic of 1893, *Chattanooga Times* publisher Adolph Ochs gained a controlling interest in the company.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 1935, Ochs was succeeded by his son-in-law, Arthur Hays Sulzberger, who began a push into European news.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Sulzberger's son Arthur Ochs Sulzberger became publisher in 1963, adapting to a changing newspaper industry and introducing radical changes.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times* was involved in the landmark 1964 U.S.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Supreme Court case *New York Times Co. v.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Sullivan*, which restricted the ability of public officials to sue the media for defamation.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 1971, *The New York Times* published the *Pentagon Papers*, an internal Department of Defense document detailing the United States's historical involvement in the Vietnam War, despite pushback from then-president Richard Nixon.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In the landmark decision *New York Times Co. v.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] United States* (1971), the Supreme Court ruled that the First Amendment guaranteed the right to publish the *Pentagon Papers*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In the 1980s, the *Times* began a two-decade progression to digital technology and launched nytimes.com in 1996.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In the 21st century, it shifted its publication online amid the global decline of newspapers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Currently, the *Times* maintains several regional bureaus staffed with journalists across six continents.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] It has expanded to several other publications, including *The New York Times Magazine*, *The New York Times International Edition*, and *The New York Times Book Review*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In addition, the paper has produced several television series, podcasts—including *The Daily*—and games through *The New York Times Games*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Among other accolades, it has been awarded the Pulitzer Prize 135 times since 1918, the most of any publication.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] However, *The New York Times* has been involved in a number of controversies in its history.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] According to a 2025 Pew Research Center study on educational differences among audiences of 30 major U.S. news outlets, *The New York Times* had the highest proportion of college-educated readers among the daily newspapers surveyed, with 56% of its audience holding at least a bachelor's degree.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] —was published on Thursday, September 18, 1851.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] after the evening edition was suspended, and the hyphen was dropped in 1896.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In August 1896, *Chattanooga Times* publisher Adolph Ochs acquired *The New-York Times*, implementing significant alterations to the newspaper's structure.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Ochs established the *Times* as a merchant's newspaper and removed the hyphen from the newspaper's name.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 1905, *The New York Times* opened Times Tower, marking expansion.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* experienced a political realignment in the 1910s amid several disagreements within the Republican Party.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times* reported on the sinking of the *Titanic*, as other newspapers were cautious about bulletins circulated by the Associated Press.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Through managing editor Carr Van Anda, the *Times* paid considerable attention to advances in science, reporting on Albert Einstein's then-obscure theory of general relativity and becoming involved in the discovery of the tomb of Tutankhamun.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In April 1935, Ochs died, leaving his son-in-law Arthur Hays Sulzberger as publisher.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The Great Depression forced Sulzberger to reduce *The New York Times*'s operations, and developments in the New York newspaper landscape resulted in the formation of larger newspapers, such as the *New York Herald Tribune* and the *New York World-Telegram*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In contrast to Ochs, Sulzberger encouraged wirephotography.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Following World War II, *The New York Times* continued to expand.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* was subject to investigations from the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee, a McCarthyist subcommittee that investigated purported communism from within press institutions.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Arthur Hays Sulzberger's decision to dismiss a copyreader who had pleaded the Fifth Amendment drew ire from within the *Times* and from external organizations.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In April 1961, Sulzberger resigned, appointing his son-in-law, The New York Times Company president Orvil Dryfoos.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Under Dryfoos, *The New York Times* established a newspaper based in Los Angeles.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 1962, the implementation of automated printing presses in response to increasing costs mounted fears over technological unemployment.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Typographical Union staged a strike in December, altering the media consumption of New Yorkers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The strike left New York with three remaining newspapers—the *Times*, the *Daily News*, and the *New York Post*—by its conclusion in March 1963.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In May, Dryfoos died of a heart ailment.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Following weeks of ambiguity, Arthur Ochs Sulzberger became *The New York Times*'s publisher.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Technological advancements leveraged by newspapers such as the *Los Angeles Times* and improvements in coverage from *The Washington Post* and *The Wall Street Journal* necessitated adaptations to nascent computing.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times* published "Heed Their Rising Voices" in 1960, a full-page advertisement purchased by supporters of Martin Luther King Jr. criticizing law enforcement in Montgomery, Alabama for their response to the civil rights movement.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Montgomery Public Safety commissioner L.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Sullivan sued the *Times* for defamation.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Supreme Court ruled that the verdict in Alabama county court and the Supreme Court of Alabama violated the First Amendment.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The decision is considered to be a landmark.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] After financial losses, *The New York Times* ended its international edition, acquiring a stake in the *Paris Herald Tribune*, forming the *International Herald Tribune*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* initially published the *Pentagon Papers*, facing opposition from then-president Richard Nixon.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The Supreme Court ruled in *The New York Times*'s favor in *New York Times Co. v.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] United States* (1971), allowing the *Times* and *The Washington Post* to publish the papers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Following years of waning interest in *The New York Times*, Sulzberger resigned in January 1992, appointing his son, Arthur Ochs Sulzberger Jr., as publisher.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Despite opposition, several employees of the *Times* had begun to access the Internet.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* published domestic terrorist Ted Kaczynski's essay *Industrial Society and Its Future* in 1995, contributing to his arrest after his brother David recognized the essay's penmanship.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Electronic Media Company was adversely affected by the dot-com crash.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* extensively covered the September 11 attacks.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The following day's print issue contained sixty-six articles, the work of over three hundred dispatched reporters.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Journalist Judith Miller was the recipient of a package containing a white powder during the 2001 anthrax attacks, furthering anxiety within *The New York Times*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In September 2002, Miller and military correspondent Michael R.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Gordon wrote an article for the *Times* claiming that Iraq had purchased aluminum tubes.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The article was cited by then-president George W.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Bush to claim that Iraq was constructing weapons of mass destruction; the theoretical use of aluminum tubes to produce nuclear material was speculation.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In March 2003, the United States invaded Iraq, beginning the Iraq War.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] During the Great Recession, *The New York Times* suffered significant fiscal difficulties as a consequence of the subprime mortgage crisis and a decline in classified advertising.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Exacerbated by Rupert Murdoch's revitalization of *The Wall Street Journal* through his acquisition of Dow Jones & Company, The New York Times Company began enacting measures to reduce the newsroom budget.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times*'s economic downturn renewed discussions of an online paywall; *The New York Times* implemented a paywall in March 2011.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Abramson succeeded Keller, continuing her characteristic investigations into corporate and government malfeasance into the *Times*'s coverage.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Following conflicts with newly appointed chief executive Mark Thompson's ambitions, Abramson was dismissed by Sulzberger Jr., who named Dean Baquet as her replacement.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Leading up to the 2016 presidential election, *The New York Times* elevated the Hillary Clinton email controversy into a national issue.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Donald Trump's upset victory contributed to an increase in subscriptions to the *Times*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times* experienced unprecedented indignation from Trump, who referred to publications such as the *Times* as "enemies of the people" at the Conservative Political Action Conference and tweeted his disdain for the newspaper and CNN.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In October 2017, *The New York Times* published an article by journalists Jodi Kantor and Megan Twohey alleging that dozens of women had accused film producer and The Weinstein Company co-chairman Harvey Weinstein of sexual misconduct.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The investigation resulted in Weinstein's resignation and conviction, precipitated the Weinstein effect, and served as a catalyst for the #MeToo movement.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Company vacated the public editor position and eliminated the copy desk in November.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Sulzberger Jr. announced his resignation in December 2017, appointing his son, A.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Trump's relationship—equally diplomatic and negative—marked Sulzberger's tenure.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In September 2018, *The New York Times* published "I Am Part of the Resistance Inside the Trump Administration", an anonymous essay by a self-described Trump administration official later revealed to be Department of Homeland Security chief of staff Miles Taylor.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The animosity—which extended to nearly three hundred instances of Trump disparaging the *Times* by May 2019—culminated in Trump ordering federal agencies to cancel their subscriptions to *The New York Times* and *The Washington Post* in October 2019.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Trump's tax returns have been the subject of three separate investigations.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, the *Times* began implementing data services and graphs.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] On May 23, 2020, *The New York Times*'s front page solely featured *U.S.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Deaths Near 100,000, An Incalculable Loss*, a subset of the 100,000 people in the United States who died of COVID-19, the first time that the *Times*'s front page lacked images since they were introduced.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Since 2020, *The New York Times* has focused on broader diversification, developing online games and producing television series.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Company acquired *The Athletic* in January 2022.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Since 1896, *The New York Times* has been published by the Ochs-Sulzberger family, having previously been published by Henry Jarvis Raymond until 1869 and by George Jones until 1896.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Adolph Ochs published the *Times* until his death in 1935, when he was succeeded by his son-in-law, Arthur Hays Sulzberger.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Sulzberger was publisher until 1961 and was succeeded by Orvil Dryfoos, his son-in-law, who served in the position until his death in 1963.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Arthur Ochs Sulzberger succeeded Dryfoos until his resignation in 1992.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] His son, Arthur Ochs Sulzberger Jr., served as publisher until 2018.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times*'s current publisher is A.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] As of 2023, the *Times*'s executive editor is Joseph Kahn and the paper's managing editors are Marc Lacey and Carolyn Ryan, having been appointed in June 2022.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times*'s deputy managing editors are Sam Dolnick, Monica Drake, and Steve Duenes, and the paper's assistant managing editors are Matthew Ericson, Jonathan Galinsky, Hannah Poferl, Sam Sifton, Karron Skog, and Michael Slackman.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] As of March 2023, The New York Times Company employs 5,800 individuals, including 1,700 journalists according to deputy managing editor Sam Dolnick.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Journalists for *The New York Times* may not run for public office, provide financial support to political candidates or causes, endorse candidates, or demonstrate public support for causes or movements.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Journalists are subject to the guidelines established in "Ethical Journalism" and "Guidelines on Integrity".
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] According to the former, *Times* journalists must abstain from using sources with a personal relationship to them and must not accept reimbursements or inducements from individuals who may be written about in *The New York Times*, with exceptions for gifts of nominal value.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The latter requires attribution and exact quotations, though exceptions are made for linguistic anomalies.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Staff writers are expected to ensure the veracity of all written claims, but may delegate researching obscure facts to the research desk.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In March 2021, the *Times* established a committee to avoid journalistic conflicts of interest with work written for *The New York Times*, following columnist David Brooks's resignation from the Aspen Institute for his undisclosed work on the initiative Weave.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Since 1940, editorial, media, and technology workers of *The New York Times* have been represented by the New York Times Guild.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The Times Guild, along with the Times Tech Guild, are represented by the NewsGuild-CWA.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 1940, Arthur Hays Sulzberger was called upon by the National Labor Relations Board amid accusations that he had discouraged Guild membership in the *Times*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Over the next few years, the Guild would ratify several contracts, expanding to editorial and news staff in 1942 and maintenance workers in 1943.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Guild has walked out several times in its history, including for six and a half hours in 1981 and in 2017, when copy editors and reporters walked out at lunchtime in response to the elimination of the copy desk.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] On December 7, 2022, the union held a one-day strike, the first interruption to *The New York Times* since 1978.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Guild reached an agreement in May 2023 to increase minimum salaries for employees and a retroactive bonus.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The Times Tech Guild is the largest technology union with collective bargaining rights in the United States.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The guild held a second strike beginning on November 4, 2024, threatening the *Times*'s coverage of the 2024 United States presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] As of August 2025, *The New York Times* has 11.8 million subscribers, with 11.3 million online-only subscribers and 580,000 print subscribers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Company intends to have 15 million subscribers by 2027.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times*'s shift towards subscription-based revenue with the debut of an online paywall in 2011 contributed to subscription revenue exceeding advertising revenue the following year, furthered by the 2016 presidential election and Donald Trump.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Company chief executive Meredith Kopit Levien stated that the average age of subscribers has remained constant.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In October 2001, *The New York Times* began publishing *DealBook*, a financial newsletter edited by Andrew Ross Sorkin.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* had intended to publish the newsletter in September, but delayed its debut following the September 11 attacks.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] A website for *DealBook* was established in March 2006.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times* began shifting towards *DealBook* as part of the newspaper's financial coverage in November 2010 with a renewed website and a presence in the *Times*'s print edition.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 2011, the *Times* began hosting the DealBook Summit, an annual conference hosted by Sorkin.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, *The New York Times* hosted the DealBook Online Summit in 2020 and 2021.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The 2022 DealBook Summit featured—among other speakers—former vice president Mike Pence and Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu, culminating in an interview with former FTX chief executive Sam Bankman-Fried; FTX had filed for bankruptcy several weeks prior.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The 2023 DealBook Summit's speakers included vice president Kamala Harris, Israeli president Isaac Herzog, and businessman Elon Musk.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In June 2010, *The New York Times* licensed the political blog *FiveThirtyEight* in a three-year agreement.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The blog, written by Nate Silver, had garnered attention during the 2008 presidential election for predicting the elections in forty-nine of fifty states.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *FiveThirtyEight* appeared on nytimes.com in August.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] According to Silver, several offers were made for the blog; Silver wrote that a merger of unequals must allow for editorial sovereignty and resources from the acquirer, comparing himself to Groucho Marx.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] According to *The New Republic*, *FiveThirtyEight* drew as much as a fifth of the traffic to nytimes.com during the 2012 presidential election.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In July 2013, *FiveThirtyEight* was sold to ESPN.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] According to Sullivan, his work was criticized by several notable political journalists.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The group Writers Against the War on Gaza wrote in the blog Mondoweiss that this has contrasted with *The New York Times* coverage of Russia's invasion of Ukraine, in which Russia is considered a threat to U.S. foreign policy interests, while Israel is considered an ally.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In February 1942, *The New York Times* crossword debuted in *The New York Times Magazine*; according to Richard Shepard, the attack on Pearl Harbor in December 1941 convinced then-publisher Arthur Hays Sulzberger of the necessity of a crossword.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In May 2016, The New York Times Company announced a partnership with startup Chef'd to form a meal delivery service that would deliver ingredients from The New York Times Cooking recipes to subscribers; Chef'd shut down in July 2018 after failing to accrue capital and secure financing.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The Hollywood Reporter* reported in September 2022 that the *Times* would expand its delivery options to US$95 cooking kits curated by chefs such as Nina Compton, Chintan Pandya, and Naoko Takei Moore.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] That month, the staff of NYT Cooking went on tour with Compton, Pandya, and Moore in Los Angeles, New Orleans, and New York City, culminating in a food festival.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In addition, *The New York Times* offered its own wine club originally operated by the Global Wine Company.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The New York Times Wine Club was established in August 2009, during a dramatic decrease in advertising revenue.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] By 2021, the wine club was managed by Lot18, a company that provides proprietary labels.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Lot18 managed the Williams Sonoma Wine Club and its own wine club Tasting Room.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] By 2017, *The New York Times* began developing a new authoring tool to its content management system known as Oak, in an attempt to further the *Times*'s visual efforts in articles and reduce the discrepancy between the mediums in print and online articles.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The system reduces the input of editors and supports additional visual mediums in an editor that resembles the appearance of the article.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Oak is based on ProseMirror, a JavaScript rich-text editor toolkit, and retains the revision tracking and commenting functionalities of *The New York Times*'s previous systems.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Additionally, Oak supports predefined article headers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 2019, Oak was updated to support collaborative editing using Firebase to update editors's cursor status.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Several Google Cloud Functions and Google Cloud Tasks allow articles to be previewed as they will be printed, and the *Times*'s primary MySQL database is regularly updated to update editors on the article status.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Since 1895, *The New York Times* has maintained a manual of style in several forms.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* was published on the *Times*'s intranet in 1999.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Journalists for *The New York Times* do not write their own headlines, but rather copy editors who specifically write headlines.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times*'s guidelines insist headline editors get to the main point of an article but avoid giving away endings, if present.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Other guidelines include using slang "sparingly", avoiding tabloid headlines, not ending a line on a preposition, article, or adjective, and chiefly, not to pun.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* states that wordplay, such as "Rubber Industry Bounces Back", is to be tested on a colleague as a canary is to be tested in a coal mine; "when no song bursts forth, start rewriting".
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] *The New York Times* has amended headlines due to controversy.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In 2019, following two back-to-back mass shootings in El Paso and Dayton, the *Times* used the headline, "Trump Urges Unity vs.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Racism", to describe then-president Donald Trump's words after the shootings.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] After criticism from *FiveThirtyEight* founder Nate Silver, the headline was changed to, "Assailing Hate But Not Guns".
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Online, *The New York Times*'s headlines do not face the same length restrictions as headlines that appear in print; print headlines must fit within a column, often six words.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Additionally, headlines must "break" properly, containing a complete thought on each line without splitting up prepositions and adverbs.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Writers may edit a headline to fit an article more aptly if further developments occur.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The *Times* uses A/B testing for articles on the front page, placing two headlines against each other.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] At the end of the test, the headlines that receives more traffic is chosen.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The headline was intentionally changed in the print version to use "wiretapped" in order to fit within the print guidelines.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The nameplate of *The New York Times* has been unaltered since 1967.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] In creating the initial nameplate, Henry Jarvis Raymond took as his model the British newspaper *The Times*, which used a Blackletter style called Textura, popularized following the fall of the Western Roman Empire and regional variations of Alcuin's script, as well as a period.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] With the change to *The New-York Times* on September 14, 1857, the nameplate followed.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] Under George Jones, the terminals of the "N", "r", and "s" were intentionally exaggerated into swashes.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The nameplate in the January 15, 1894, issue trimmed the terminals once more, smoothed the edges, and turned the stem supporting the "T" into an ornament.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The hyphen was dropped on December 1, 1896, after Adolph Ochs purchased the paper.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The descender of the "h" was shortened on December 30, 1914.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p01] The largest change to the nameplate was introduced on February 21, 1967, when type designer Ed Benguiat redesigned the logo, most prominently turning the arrow ornament into a diamond.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] As of December 2023, *The New York Times* has printed sixty thousand issues, a statistic represented in the paper's masthead to the right of the volume number, the *Times*'s years in publication written in Roman numerals.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The volume and issues are separated by four dots representing the edition number of that issue; on the day of the 2000 presidential election, the *Times* was revised four separate times, necessitating the use of an em dash in place of an ellipsis.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The em dash issue was printed hundreds times over before being replaced by the one-dot issue.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Despite efforts by newsroom employees to recycle copies sent to *The New York Times*'s office, several copies were kept, including one put on display at the Museum at The Times.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] From February 7, 1898, to December 31, 1999, the *Times*'s issue number was incorrect by five hundred issues, an error suspected by *The Atlantic* to be the result of a careless front page type editor.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The misreporting was noticed by news editor Aaron Donovan, who was calculating the number of issues in a spreadsheet and noticed the discrepancy.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] *The New York Times* celebrated fifty thousand issues on March 14, 1995, an observance that should have occurred on July 26, 1996.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In cases where two major events occur on the same day or immediately after each other, *The New York Times* has used a "paddle wheel" headline, where both headlines are used but split by a line.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The term dates back to August 8, 1959, when it was revealed that the United States was monitoring Soviet missile firings and when Explorer 6—shaped like a paddle wheel—launched.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Since then, the paddle wheel has been used several times, including on January 21, 1981, when Ronald Reagan was sworn in minutes before Iran released fifty-two American hostages, ending the Iran hostage crisis.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] At the time, most newspapers favored the end of the hostage crisis, but the *Times* placed the inauguration above the crisis.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Since 1997, *The New York Times*'s primary distribution center is located in College Point, Queens.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The College Point distribution center prints 300,000 to 800,000 newspapers daily.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] On most occasions, presses start before 11 p.m. and finish before 3 a.m.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] A robotic crane grabs a roll of newsprint and several rollers ensure ink can be printed on paper.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The final newspapers are wrapped in plastic and shipped out.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] As of 2018, the College Point facility accounted for 41% of production.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Other copies are printed at 26 other publications, such as *The Atlanta Journal-Constitution*, *The Dallas Morning News*, *The Santa Fe New Mexican*, and the (Louisville) *Courier Journal*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] With the decline of newspapers, particularly regional publications, the *Times* must travel further; for example, newspapers for Hawaii are flown from San Francisco on United Airlines, and Sunday papers are flown from Los Angeles on Hawaiian Airlines.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Computer glitches, mechanical issues, and weather phenomena affect circulation but do not stop the paper from reaching customers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The College Point facility prints over two dozen other papers, including *The Wall Street Journal* and *USA Today*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *New York Times* website is hosted at nytimes.com.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] It has undergone several major redesigns and infrastructure developments since its debut.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In April 2006, *The New York Times* redesigned its website with an emphasis on multimedia.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In preparation for Super Tuesday in February 2008, the *Times* developed a live election system using the Associated Press's File Transfer Protocol (FTP) service and a Ruby on Rails application; nytimes.com experienced its largest traffic on Super Tuesday and the day after.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The NYTimes application debuted with the introduction of the App Store on July 10, 2008.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] *Engadget*'s Scott McNulty wrote critically of the app, negatively comparing it to *The New York Times*'s mobile website.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] An iPad version with select articles was released on April 3, 2010, with the release of the first-generation iPad.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In October, *The New York Times* expanded NYT Editors' Choice to include the paper's full articles.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *Times* applications on iPhone and iPad began offering in-app subscriptions in July 2011.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *Times* released a web application for iPad—featuring a format summarizing trending headlines on Twitter—and a Windows 8 application in October 2012.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Efforts to ensure profitability through an online magazine and a "Need to Know" subscription emerged in *Adweek* in July 2013.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In March 2014, *The New York Times* announced three applications—NYT Now, an application that offers pertinent news in a blog format, and two unnamed applications, later known as NYT Opinion and NYT Cooking—to diversify its product laterals.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In October 2021, *The New York Times* began testing "New York Times Audio", an application featuring podcasts from the *Times*, audio versions of articles—including from other publications through Audm, and archives from *This American Life*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The application debuted in May 2023 exclusively on iOS for *Times* subscribers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] New York Times Audio includes exclusive podcasts such as *The Headlines*, a daily news recap, and *Shorts*, short audio stories under ten minutes.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In addition, a "Reporter Reads" section features *Times* journalists reading their articles and providing commentary.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In January 2022, The New York Times Company acquired *Wordle*, a word game developed by Josh Wardle in 2021, at a valuation in the "low-seven figures".
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The acquisition was proposed by David Perpich, a member of the Sulzberger family who proposed the purchase to Knight over Slack after reading about the game.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] *The Washington Post* purportedly considered acquiring *Wordle*, according to *Vanity Fair*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] At the 2022 Game Developers Conference, Wardle stated that he was overwhelmed by the volume of *Wordle* facsimiles and overzealous monetization practices in other games.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Concerns over *The New York Times* monetizing *Wordle* by implementing a paywall mounted; *Wordle* is a client-side browser game and can be played offline by downloading its webpage.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] *Wordle* moved to the *Times*'s servers and website in February.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The game was added to the NYT Games application in August, necessitating it be rewritten in the JavaScript library React.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In November, *The New York Times* announced that Tracy Bennett would be the *Wordle*'s editor.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In February 2016, *The New York Times* introduced a Spanish website, *The New York Times en Español*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The website, intended to be read on mobile devices, would contain translated articles from the *Times* and reporting from journalists based in Mexico City.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *Times en Español*'s style editor is Paulina Chavira, who has advocated for pluralistic Spanish to accommodate the variety of nationalities in the newsroom's journalists and wrote a stylebook for *The New York Times en Español*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Articles the *Times* intends to publish in Spanish are sent to a translation agency and adapted for Spanish writing conventions; the present progressive tense may be used for forthcoming events in English, but other tenses are preferable in Spanish.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *Times en Español* consults the Real Academia Española and Fundéu and frequently modifies the use of diacritics—such as using an acute accent for the Cártel de Sinaloa but not the Cartel de Medellín—and using the gender-neutral pronoun *elle*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Headlines in *The New York Times en Español* are not capitalized.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *Times en Español* publishes *El Times*, a newsletter led by Elda Cantú intended for all Spanish speakers.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In September 2019, *The New York Times* ended *The New York Times en Español*'s separate operations.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] A study published in *The Translator* in 2023 found that the *Times en Español* engaged in tabloidization.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In June 2012, *The New York Times* introduced a Chinese website, 纽约时报中文, in response to Chinese editions created by *The Wall Street Journal* and the *Financial Times*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Then-foreign editor Joseph Kahn assisted in the establishment of cn.nytimes.com, an effort that contributed to his appointment as executive editor in April 2022.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In October 2012, 纽约时报中文 published an article detailing the wealth of then-premier Wen Jiabao's family.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In response, the government of China blocked access to nytimes.com and cn.nytimes.com and references to the *Times* and Wen were censored on microblogging service Sina Weibo.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In March 2015, a mirror of 纽约时报中文 and the website for GreatFire were the targets for a government-sanctioned distributed denial of service attack on GitHub in March 2015, disabling access to the service for several days.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Chinese authorities requested the removal of *The New York Times*'s news applications from the App Store in December 2016.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] As of 2023, *The New York Times* has received 137 Pulitzer Prizes, the most of any publication.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] A study published in *Science, Technology, & Human Values* in 2013 found that *The New York Times* received more citations in academic journals than the *American Sociological Review*, *Research Policy*, or the *Harvard Law Review*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] With sixteen million unique records, the *Times* is the third-most referenced source in Common Crawl, a collection of online material used in datasets such as GPT-3, behind Wikipedia and a United States patent database.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Since 2003, studies analyzing coverage of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict in the *New York Times* have demonstrated a bias against Palestinians and in favor of Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In December 2023, *The New York Times* published an investigation titled "'Screams Without Words': How Hamas Weaponized Sexual Violence on Oct.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] 7", alleging that Hamas weaponized sexual and gender-based violence during its armed incursion on Israel.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In addition, protesters blocked *The New York Times*'s distribution center March 14, 2024 and executive editor Joseph Kahn's residence was splattered with red paint on August 25, 2025.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The collective Writers Against the War on Gaza, which publishes the mock publication *The New York War Crimes*, has been associated with protests against *The New York Times*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Among the initial signatories, about 150 had previously contributed to the *Times*.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In February 2023, nearly one thousand current and former *Times* writers and contributors wrote an open letter addressed to standards editor Philip B.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Corbett, criticizing the paper's coverage of transgender, non⁠-⁠binary, and gender-nonconforming people; some of the *Times*'s articles have been cited in state legislatures attempting to justify criminalizing gender-affirming care.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] According to former *Times* journalist Billie Jean Sweeney, a push for writers to challenge "every aspect of being trans", ranging from gender-inclusive language to access to medical care, came from the top in 2022 after leadership was handed over to A.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] Sulzberger, Joe Kahn, and Carolyn Ryan; as part of an effort to win good will with the Trump campaign without incurring backlash from the general populace.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] The *Times* has continually denied any bias in its reporting, insisting that its coverage of "fiercely contested medical and legal debates" is fair and balanced, and that it would not tolerate journalists protesting its transgender coverage.
[src:the-new-york-times/the-new-york-times-p02] In June 2026, civil rights attorney Alejandra Caraballo published a study in her newsletter, *The Dissident*, which analyzed 3,242 articles that were published in the *Times* between 2014 and 2026.
